Controversial take: Most code comments are bad.

Not all. Most.

𝗕𝗮𝗱 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁𝘀:

```
// increment i by 1
i++;

// get user
const user = getUser();

// TODO: fix this later (from 2019)
```

𝗚𝗼𝗼𝗱 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁𝘀:

```
// We use setTimeout here because the DOM needs
// to render before we can measure element height

// Business rule: Premium users skip rate limiting
// See: JIRA-1234
```

𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲:

Bad comments explain WHAT.
Good comments explain WHY.

𝗕𝗲𝘁𝘁𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝗻 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁𝘀:

- Better variable names
- Smaller functions
- Code that reads like English

𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗿𝘂𝗹𝗲:

If you need a comment to explain what code does, rewrite the code.

Save comments for the weird stuff that NEEDS explanation.

Your future self will thank you.

Not handling errors properly.

I see this constantly:

app.get('/user/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await db.findUser(req.params.id)
  res.json(user)
})

What happens when db.findUser throws? Your server crashes. Or worse, hangs forever.

𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗳𝗶𝘅:

𝟭. Wrap async routes:
app.get('/user/:id', asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {...}))

𝟮. Add error middleware LAST:
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  res.status(500).json({ error: err.message })
})

𝟯. Validate inputs:
if (!req.params.id) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'ID required' })

𝟰. Handle 404s:
app.use((req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' }))

Express doesn't catch async errors by default. It's a design choice from 2010.

Handle your errors or your errors will handle you.

Same syntax. Different contexts.

... can expand or collect. Depends where you use it.

𝗦𝗽𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗱: Expands things out

const arr1 = [1, 2, 3]
const arr2 = [...arr1, 4, 5] // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

const obj1 = { a: 1 }
const obj2 = { ...obj1, b: 2 } // { a: 1, b: 2 }

𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘁: Collects things together

function sum(...nums) {
  return nums.reduce((a, b) => a + b)
}
sum(1, 2, 3, 4) // nums is [1, 2, 3, 4]

const { a, ...rest } = { a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 }
// a is 1, rest is { b: 2, c: 3 }

𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗿𝘂𝗹𝗲:

On the RIGHT side of = ? Spread (expanding)
On the LEFT side of = ? Rest (collecting)

In function parameters? Rest (collecting arguments)
In function calls? Spread (expanding array)

Once you see it, you can't unsee it.

It's not two operators. It's one operator with two jobs.

Clean up after yourself.

Memory leaks in JavaScript usually come from three places:

𝟭. 𝗙𝗼𝗿𝗴𝗼𝘁𝘁𝗲𝗻 𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗹𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗻𝗲𝗿𝘀

window.addEventListener('scroll', handler)
// Component unmounts, listener stays

𝗙𝗶𝘅: Remove in cleanup
useEffect(() => {
  window.addEventListener('scroll', handler)
  return () => window.removeEventListener('scroll', handler)
}, [])

𝟮. 𝗨𝗻𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗿𝘃𝗮𝗹𝘀/𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗲𝗼𝘂𝘁𝘀

setInterval(fetchData, 5000)
// Tab closed, interval keeps running

𝗙𝗶𝘅: Clear on cleanup
const id = setInterval(fn, 5000)
return () => clearInterval(id)

𝟯. 𝗖𝗹𝗼𝘀𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗵𝗼𝗹𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗿𝗲𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲𝘀

Storing references to DOM elements or large objects in closures that outlive their usefulness.

𝗗𝗲𝗯𝘂𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴:

Chrome DevTools → Memory → Take heap snapshot
Look for growing detached DOM trees

The garbage collector is smart but not psychic. Help it out.

Think about all the states, not just success.

Every async operation has at least 4 states:

𝗜𝗱𝗹𝗲: Nothing happening yet
𝗟𝗼𝗮𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗴: Request in progress
𝗦𝘂𝗰𝗰𝗲𝘀𝘀: Data received
𝗘𝗿𝗿𝗼𝗿: Something failed

Most people handle 2 of these. Maybe 3.

𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗻𝗮𝗶𝘃𝗲 𝘄𝗮𝘆:

const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false)
const [data, setData] = useState(null)
const [error, setError] = useState(null)

Three pieces of state that can conflict.

𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝘁𝘁𝗲𝗿 𝘄𝗮𝘆:

type State = 
  | { status: 'idle' }
  | { status: 'loading' }
  | { status: 'success', data: User }
  | { status: 'error', error: Error }

One source of truth. Impossible invalid states.

𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝘄𝗮𝘆:

Use React Query or SWR.

const { data, isLoading, error } = useQuery(...)

They handle the state machine for you.

Loading states are UX. Bad loading states feel broken. Good ones feel fast.
